# pyenv
#   For a library or package, you might want to ignore these files since the user is
#   responsible for setting up their own environment. For a binary, app or service,
#   you might want to commit them.
# .python-version

# pipenv
#   According to pypa/pipenv#598, it is recommended to commit Pipfile.lock to version control.
#   However, in ideal cases, where pipenv is used for development, you may ignore it.
# .env
# .venv
# env/
# venv/
# Pipfile.lock

# poetry
#   Similar to Pipenv, poetry.lock is of high interest and recommended to be committed.
#   https://python-poetry.org/docs/basic-usage/#commit-your-poetrylock-file-to-version-control
# poetry.lock

# pdm
#   Similar to Pipenv and Poetry, pdm.lock is of high interest and recommended to be committed.
